<!--
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 3: The Burning Platform

Let me ask you a provocative question. If you look at how your engineering teams work today — the sprint ceremonies, the review gates, the approval chains — how much of that was designed *this year*? How much was designed five years ago?

I've talked to teams at ICICI, Bajaj, HDFC. Smart teams. Great engineers. But they're running a process that was designed before GitHub Copilot existed. Before ChatGPT. Before AI agents could write and review code in seconds.

Think about it this way. Writing code used to be expensive — it took days. Now it takes minutes. That's the "Code is cheap" shift.

Running that code — spinning up infra, deploying, testing — was complex. Now agents do it continuously. "Execution is fast."

But here's what didn't change: the meeting where eight people debate *which* feature to build next. The architect sign-off that takes three weeks. The compliance review that nobody knows who owns.

Judgement is still slow. And now that AI has made everything else fast, the slowness of human decision-making is exposed like never before.

The bottleneck didn't move downstream. It moved *upstream*.

This is the burning platform. Not because AI is taking jobs — but because your *process* hasn't caught up with your *tools*.
-->

