<!--
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 5: How Agents Work

Let me explain how an AI agent actually works — because there's a lot of confusion between "AI autocomplete" and "AI agent."

Copilot autocomplete is like a smart typist. You type, it suggests the next word. Helpful. Nice. But it's not an agent.

An agent is different. You give it a goal — not a prompt — and it figures out how to get there.

Example: You say "Build me a loan intake API for retail customers." An agent doesn't just start typing code. It first decomposes the problem: What are the requirements? What's the data model? What security constraints apply? Then it starts calling skills — it might call a tool to look up your org's approved tech stack, call another to generate a test plan, call a third to check naming conventions.

The big shift is this: instead of a human doing all that decomposition manually in a planning session... the agent does it. The human writes the goal — the "intent" — and reviews the output.

Now here's the beautiful part. In an AIDLC-mature organisation, all those rules the agent follows — the naming conventions, the security standards, the quality bar — they've been written down as specifications. Once.

So every time a new feature is built, the agent applies the same institutional wisdom. Automatically. No tribal knowledge. No "ask Ramesh because he's been here 7 years."

Ramesh, by the way, is now a Decision Encoder. More on that in a few slides.
-->

