<!--
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 6: AIDLC Pipeline

This is AIDLC — the AI-Driven Development Lifecycle.

Five stages. Same as your current SDLC. Requirements, Design, Code, Test, Deploy. Nothing revolutionary about the stages themselves.

What's revolutionary is *who does the work* at each stage.

In a traditional SDLC, humans do the heavy lifting at every stage. An agent is maybe helping with autocomplete. In AIDLC, agents handle the execution at every stage — while humans set the direction.

The bottom row is important. The human's job is to write down the intent and quality bar clearly enough that an agent can act on it. The agent's job is to execute that intent — reliably, consistently, at scale.

Here's the maturity insight: in the beginning, humans are still doing most of the decision-making. They're just using agents as faster executors. That's Level 1.

As you progress, you start encoding more decisions into the spec — "always use managed identity," "never expose port 22," "our microservices follow this naming pattern." The agent applies these rules automatically. Level 2.

At Level 3, agents are orchestrating entire workflows. The human reviews outcomes, not steps.

At Level 4 — the frontier — agents are even suggesting improvements to the process itself.

Where is your org today? Most of the BFSI companies in India are at Level 1 and a half. Comfortable with the tools but not yet encoding the decisions. That's what we're helping you do.
-->

