<!--
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 8: Agile vs Agentic

I need to say something that might be slightly controversial in a room full of Certified Scrum Masters.

The two-week sprint was a great innovation. In 2001. It was designed to shorten the feedback loop in a world where software took six months to ship. Sprint planning, daily standups, retrospectives — all ceremonies designed to make humans coordinate faster.

But here's the thing: agents don't need a standup. They don't need a retrospective. They don't need two weeks to find out if the code works. They find out in 30 seconds when the test pipeline runs.

I'm not saying agile is dead. I'm saying the *ceremonies* were compensating for the limitations of human coordination. As agents take over execution, those limitations change.

The right side of this slide is what an AIDLC org looks like. You still have direction-setting. You still have planning. But it's specification-driven, not ceremony-driven. You write the spec once — "this feature should do X, follow Y standards, deploy to Z" — and agents execute it continuously until it's done.

"Humans watch the pipeline" — I love this one. How many hours has your team spent this month watching a deployment pipeline waiting for it to go green? That time is gone. Agents watch pipelines. Humans set the policy for what happens when it goes red.

This is not the future. Teams at Microsoft, GitHub, and our early customers are doing this *now*.
-->

