<!--
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 9: Role Evolution

People always ask me: "Will AI take our developer jobs?"

Short answer: No. Long answer: your job description is getting a rewrite.

Let me tell you about the most valuable engineer at an AIDLC-mature organisation. It's not the person who writes the most code. It's the person who writes the best *specification* — the one that agents can follow reliably without asking for clarification every five minutes.

Think about the Product Manager. Their job was to write PRDs — Product Requirements Documents. Now? Their job is to write agent-ready specifications. Not a 40-page Word document. A clear, structured description of what "done" looks like that an AI agent can actually act on. That's harder than it sounds. And it's more valuable than ever.

The Platform Engineer used to build shared infrastructure. Now they build the guardrails — the Copilot instructions, the GitHub rulesets, the Azure Policy definitions. They're encoding the organisation's engineering culture into machine-readable form. This is incredibly high-leverage work.

The Tech Lead used to make architectural decisions in meetings. Now they encode those decisions — once — as agent specifications. And every team benefits automatically.

Ramesh from my earlier example? He's now a Decision Encoder. He's writing down 15 years of institutional knowledge in a form that agents can apply at scale. His knowledge finally has leverage. That's a promotion, not a demotion.

The roles haven't disappeared. They've become more strategic.
-->

