<!--
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 11: git-ape

OK so we now have a working prototype. That's great. But here's what happens in most organisations: the prototype lives in a developer's laptop for three months while security review, compliance review, and infra provisioning happen in parallel slow lanes.

git-ape solves this. It's an open-source project on GitHub — azure/git-ape — that I and the team have built specifically for this problem.

What does it do? It's a multi-agent platform engineering framework built on GitHub Copilot. You talk to it like you talk to a colleague: "@git-ape, deploy the loan intake microservice to Azure India South."

And it does four things:

One: It interviews you. Not a human interview — it asks the right questions about your requirements, your security constraints, your budget. 

Two: Before touching anything, it generates a complete report. ARM template, architecture diagram, estimated monthly cost in rupees, security posture check. You see everything before anything happens.

Three: It stops. And asks you to confirm. Nothing — absolutely nothing — goes to Azure without your explicit "yes." This is critical for regulated industries.

Four: It deploys, and then validates. It checks that HTTPS is enforced, managed identity is configured, Application Insights is connected. And it logs everything — every deployment saved under .azure/deployments/ — which your auditors will love.

And the security stack? Checkov runs on every IaC template. Microsoft Defender for DevOps is in the pipeline. Azure Policy acts as the final backstop. This is compliance by architecture, not compliance by audit.
-->

