<!--
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 12: Guardrails

This slide is specifically important for the BFSI folks in the room. Your regulators — RBI, SEBI — have very specific requirements. Data residency, encryption, access controls, audit trails. How do you make sure every deployment, from every team, meets those requirements?

In a traditional org, you have a compliance checklist. An engineer fills it out. A compliance officer reviews it. If they missed something, you find out three weeks before go-live. Not great.

In an AIDLC org with git-ape, compliance is embedded at five layers.

Layer 5 — the bottom — is context. Copilot Spaces curate what the AI knows about your environment. Your approved architecture patterns, your security policies, your Azure region constraints. The agent starts from this knowledge.

Layer 4 — Copilot custom instructions. In your repository, you write: "Always use managed identity. Never open SSH to 0.0.0.0/0. Tag all resources with cost-centre." These travel with the code. Version-controlled. Peer-reviewed. Updated in a PR.

Layer 3 — Copilot agent skills. Reusable capabilities — check naming conventions, look up your CMDB, validate cost thresholds. Any agent can invoke these.

Layer 2 — GitHub Actions. Every IaC template runs through Checkov. Microsoft Defender for DevOps checks for vulnerabilities. Non-compliant code is blocked before merge.

Layer 1 — Azure Policy. The final backstop. Even if something slipped through, Azure Policy denies the deployment. Your security team sleeps well.

Five layers. By the time a deployment reaches production, it has passed through five independent compliance checks. That's the architecture of trust.
-->

