<!--
SPEAKER NOTES — Slide 16: ROI and DORA

Let's talk numbers. Because in this room, you're all going to have to justify this investment to someone — a CFO, a board, a risk committee.

DORA metrics are the industry standard for measuring software delivery performance. Google and DVSM have been running this research for years. AIDLC-mature organisations consistently hit elite DORA bands.

Deployment Frequency: 3 to 5 times faster. That means features that used to ship monthly now ship weekly. Or features that shipped weekly now ship daily.

Lead Time for Changes: down 65%. The time from "I have an idea" to "it's in production" — that gap shrinks dramatically when agents handle the execution steps.

Change Failure Rate: down 45%. Because agents apply the same quality checks every time. No tired Friday afternoon deployments that break things. No "I forgot to update the config" rollbacks.

MTTR — Mean Time to Restore: down 50%. Because with drift detection and automated rollback, you find out about problems faster and fix them faster.

But I want to add two metrics that DORA doesn't capture.

Spec-to-Ship Cycle Time: From the moment you have an approved specification to the moment it's running in production — that should be hours, not weeks. In an AIDLC org, it often is.

Developer Happiness: This one's hard to quantify, but easy to see. When engineers stop spending their days writing boilerplate and watching pipelines... they start doing the creative, high-leverage work they actually wanted to do when they got into this field. Retention goes up. Innovation goes up.

You can't manage what you don't measure. Start with deployment frequency and lead time. Those two alone will tell you whether your AIDLC investment is working.
-->

